l laminae"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms a complete ring at vertebral level C6\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the cricoid cartilage. It is unique among laryngeal cartilages in forming a complete ring around the airway. The cartilage has a broad posterior lamina and a narrow anterior arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreates an incomplete posterior ring\u003C/strong\u003E - The cricoid forms a complete, not incomplete, ring\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms a C-shaped cartilage at vertebral level C4\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the thyroid cartilage, which is located higher in the neck\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttaches directly to the first tracheal ring\u003C/strong\u003E - While close to the first tracheal ring, they are connected by cricotracheal ligament, not direct attachment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains paired lateral laminae\u003C/strong\u003E - The cricoid has a single posterior lamina, not paired lateral ones\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cricoid cartilage is an important landmark for emergency airway procedures and provides attachment points for several intrinsic laryngeal muscles, including the posterior and lateral cricoarytenoid muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cricoid cartilage forms a complete ring around the airway at vertebral level C6.","The cricoid cartilage has a broad posterior lamina and narrow anterior arch.","The cricoid cartilage provides attachment for intrinsic laryngeal muscles including the posterior and lateral cricoarytenoid muscles."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAnatomical dis